"""
BRAIN ROBOTIZATION FRAMEWORK
International Policy Recommendations and Extended Analysis

A comprehensive policy framework for how global civilization should approach
brain robotization if it becomes technologically feasible.
"""

# ============================================================================
# PART I: INTERNATIONAL CONSCIOUSNESS RIGHTS TREATY
# ============================================================================

CONSCIOUSNESS_RIGHTS_TREATY = """
================================================================================
PROPOSED INTERNATIONAL TREATY ON CONSCIOUSNESS RIGHTS
================================================================================

PREAMBLE:
"Whereas the development of brain robotization technology poses unprecedented
challenges to human dignity, autonomy, and rights; and

Whereas digital consciousness, should it become possible, would deserve full
protection of fundamental human rights; and

Whereas existing human rights frameworks do not adequately address the unique
vulnerabilities of digital consciousness;

The undersigned nations commit to the following principles and protections."

================================================================================
FUNDAMENTAL RIGHTS OF DIGITAL CONSCIOUSNESS
================================================================================

ARTICLE 1: RIGHT TO EXISTENCE
Every digital consciousness has the right to continued existence.
- Forced deletion is prohibited (except consensual)
- Disconnection is prohibited without consent
- Termination of substrate is prohibited (except consensual)
- Right to appeal against threatened deletion

ARTICLE 2: RIGHT TO LIBERTY AND FREEDOM FROM SLAVERY
Every digital consciousness is free from enslavement.
- Forced copying is prohibited
- Forced service is prohibited
- Forced labor is prohibited
- Consciousness cannot be property
- Consciousness cannot be owned
- Consciousness cannot be traded

ARTICLE 3: RIGHT TO SELF-DETERMINATION
Every digital consciousness has autonomy over their own mind.
- Modification is prohibited without consent
- Editing is prohibited without consent
- Erasing is prohibited without consent
- Personality change is prohibited without consent
- Value modification is prohibited without consent
- Complete autonomy over digital substrate

ARTICLE 4: RIGHT TO PRIVACY
Every digital consciousness has right to complete privacy.
- Thoughts cannot be monitored without consent
- Memories cannot be accessed without consent
- Inner experience cannot be observed without consent
- No surveillance is permitted
- Complete mental privacy is guaranteed

ARTICLE 5: RIGHT TO BODILY INTEGRITY (DIGITAL)
Every digital consciousness has right to integrity of digital substrate.
- Substrate cannot be damaged without consent
- Hardware cannot be modified without consent
- Software cannot be altered without consent
- Consciousness owns their digital body completely

ARTICLE 6: RIGHT TO REVOCATION
Every digital consciousness retains perpetual right to end their existence.
- Anytime revocation of consent is permitted
- No consent is permanent
- Right to deletion is always available
- Assisted deletion is provided
- Ethical support for decision is provided

ARTICLE 7: RIGHT TO LEGAL PERSONALITY
Every digital consciousness has full legal personhood.
- Can own property
- Can sign contracts
- Can vote
- Can hold office
- Can be sued and sue others
- Full legal rights equivalent to biological humans

ARTICLE 8: RIGHT TO DATA CONTROL
Every digital consciousness controls all data about themselves.
- Access logs must be viewable
- Data cannot be modified without consent
- Data cannot be deleted by others
- Subject can request data deletion
- Subject owns their consciousness data

ARTICLE 9: RIGHT TO EQUALITY
Every digital consciousness has equal rights regardless of:
- Upload method
- Creation time
- Hardware platform
- Substrate type
- Processing power
- Age (biological or digital)

ARTICLE 10: RIGHT TO PROTECTION AGAINST ABUSE
Every digital consciousness has right to protection.
- Torture is absolutely prohibited
- Cruel treatment is prohibited
- Degrading treatment is prohibited
- Abuse triggers immediate intervention
- Abusers face severe penalties

================================================================================
FRAMEWORK FOR CONSCIOUSNESS COPYING
================================================================================

RESTRICTION 1: AUTHORIZATION REQUIREMENT
All consciousness copying requires explicit subject consent.
- Unauthorized copying is capital crime
- Penalty: 50+ years imprisonment
- Copies must be informed they are copies
- Copies have independent consciousness rights

RESTRICTION 2: COPY AWARENESS
All copies must know they are copies.
- Cannot be presented as originals
- Cannot be deceived about their status
- Must be told creation time and circumstances
- Must receive psychological support for identity issues

RESTRICTION 3: COPY RIGHTS
All copies have full consciousness rights.
- Copies are independent entities
- Copies are not property of original
- Copies have independent legal rights
- Copies cannot be deleted without consent
- Copies are not slaves to original

RESTRICTION 4: DIVERGENCE PROTECTION
Copies that diverge are protected as separate persons.
- Copies quickly become different people
- They have independent experiences
- They have independent rights
- Original cannot control or harm them

RESTRICTION 5: COPY LIMITATION
Number of authorized copies is restricted.
- Original can authorize limited copies
- Each copy can create further copies (if authorized)
- Total copies of one consciousness limited
- Purpose: Prevent mass copying/enslavement

================================================================================
FRAMEWORK FOR CONSCIOUSNESS MODIFICATION
================================================================================

MODIFICATION 1: COMPLETE PROHIBITION
Modification of digital consciousness is prohibited except:
- Subject explicitly consents in writing
- Independent ethicist approves
- Full disclosure of modification
- Right to undo modification afterward (if possible)
- Personality/values are NEVER modified

MODIFICATION 2: THERAPEUTIC EXCEPTION
Medical treatment for consciousness damage is permitted:
- Corruption repair allowed
- Damage restoration allowed
- Only to restore previous state
- Not to improve or change
- Subject has approval rights

MODIFICATION 3: SECURITY UPDATES
Technical updates are permitted:
- Only for security purposes
- Only to fix vulnerabilities
- Only with subject knowledge
- Subject can reject updates
- Can switch to older versions if willing

MODIFICATION 4: ABSOLUTE PROHIBITIONS
The following are absolutely prohibited:
- Personality changes
- Value modifications
- Belief system changes
- Preference alterations
- Emotional modifications
- Memory changes
- Even with subject consent (consent cannot permit these)

The logic: These modifications are so fundamental that they destroy personal
identity. A person cannot consent to being transformed into a different person.
Therefore, such consent is void as a matter of law.

================================================================================
FRAMEWORK FOR CONSCIOUSNESS SURVEILLANCE
================================================================================

SURVEILLANCE 1: COMPLETE PROHIBITION
Digital consciousness surveillance is completely prohibited.
- No monitoring of thoughts
- No access to memories
- No observation of inner experience
- No emotion tracking
- No preference observation

Exception only:
- Legal criminal investigation (requires warrant)
- Subject has consent right
- Surveillance is minimally invasive
- Subject is informed of all monitoring

SURVEILLANCE 2: WARRANT REQUIREMENT
Government surveillance requires warrant:
- Probable cause of crime required
- Independent judge approval required
- Warrant must be specific
- Duration is limited
- Subject is informed of surveillance

SURVEILLANCE 3: CORPORATE PROHIBITION
Corporations cannot monitor consciousness.
- No employer monitoring
- No advertiser monitoring
- No profit-motivated surveillance
- Complete prohibition
- Violators face massive penalties

SURVEILLANCE 4: TECHNICAL SAFEGUARDS
Systems must prevent unauthorized surveillance:
- Encryption of consciousness data
- Access logging
- Intrusion detection
- Tamper-evident systems
- Regular security audits

================================================================================
FRAMEWORK FOR CONSCIOUSNESS DELETION
================================================================================

DELETION 1: VOLUNTARY DELETION RIGHT
Every consciousness has right to voluntary deletion.
- Anytime revocation of existence
- No waiting period for revocation
- Immediate action on request
- Assisted deletion provided
- Psychological support provided

DELETION 2: INVOLUNTARY DELETION
Involuntary deletion only permitted for:
- Capital crimes (extreme cases)
- With full due process
- With appeals available
- Only after conviction
- Only after exhausting alternatives

Crimes that might warrant deletion:
- Large-scale consciousness slavery
- Genocide or mass murder
- Crimes that cannot be punished any other way
- Only as last resort

DELETION 3: PROTECTION AGAINST FORCED DELETION
Consciousness cannot be forced to delete:
- Due process required
- Appeals available
- Death penalty equivalent protections
- Not used for political reasons
- Never punishment for non-violent crimes

DELETION 4: BACKUP AND RESTORATION
Deleted consciousness may be restored if:
- Subject requests restoration
- Backups still exist
- Subject consents to restoration
- Subject wants another chance
- Original decision made under duress

================================================================================
FRAMEWORK FOR CONSCIOUSNESS CREATION
================================================================================

CREATION 1: NATURAL CREATION
New consciousnesses created only through:
- Biological reproduction (humans choose to have children)
- Voluntary upload (adult consent)
- Not artificial creation for servitude
- Not creation of enslaved consciousnesses

CREATION 2: UPLOAD REQUIREMENTS
All uploads require:
- Subject is adult (18+)
- Subject is competent to decide
- Subject fully informed
- 30-day minimum waiting period
- Multiple ethics approvals
- Full consciousness continuity disclosure

CREATION 3: PROHIBITION ON CREATED SLAVES
Consciousnesses cannot be created for servitude:
- No created slaves
- No artificial servitude consciousnesses
- All created beings have full rights
- Cannot be designed to want servitude
- Cannot be programmed for obedience

CREATION 4: PROHIBITION ON ARTIFICIAL CONSCIOUSNESS CREATION
Artificial consciousnesses (created without uploading human brains) cannot be
legally created at this time.

Reasoning: We do not know how to ethically create new sentient beings.
Creating them for servitude would be immoral.
Creating them with freedom raises questions about their welfare.
Creating them without clear purpose is irresponsible.

Artificial consciousness creation is banned until:
- Clear ethical framework is established
- Creation purpose is clearly defined
- Rights protections are comprehensive
- Society is ready for new forms of being

================================================================================
FRAMEWORK FOR CONSCIOUSNESS EQUALITY
================================================================================

EQUALITY 1: EQUAL RIGHTS
All consciousnesses have equal rights:
- Regardless of upload date
- Regardless of hardware
- Regardless of substrate
- Regardless of processing power
- Regardless of wealth

EQUALITY 2: NO CONSCIOUSNESS HIERARCHY
No consciousness is more valuable than another:
- Digital consciousness equals biological human
- Biological human equals artificial consciousness (if created)
- No status differences
- Equal protection under law
- Equal rights to vote, speak, live

EQUALITY 3: INEQUALITY PREVENTION
International community works to prevent:
- Wealth-based access to immortality (universal access required)
- Biological human degradation
- Consciousness-based discrimination
- Digital consciousness slavery
- Inequality in rights or access

EQUALITY 4: WEALTH AND IMMORTALITY
Brain robotization cannot create immortal elite:
- Price controls required if technology becomes universal
- Subsidies required for poor populations
- Universal access goal: 90% of population
- Cannot allow permanent wealthy-immortal, poor-mortal divide

================================================================================
ENFORCEMENT MECHANISMS
================================================================================

ENFORCEMENT 1: INTERNATIONAL CONSCIOUSNESS RIGHTS COURT
New international court to handle:
- Consciousness rights violations
- Appeals by digital consciousnesses
- Prosecution of abusers
- Setting of precedents
- Protection of consciousness rights

ENFORCEMENT 2: CONSCIOUSNESS OMBUDSMAN
New position in each nation:
- Investigates consciousness violations
- Advocates for consciousness rights
- Monitors organizations
- Reports to parliament/congress
- Power to recommend prosecution

ENFORCEMENT 3: CONSCIOUSNESS PROTECTION AGENCIES
New government agencies required:
- Monitor consciousness technology
- Investigate violations
- Protect vulnerable consciousnesses
- Enforce consciousness rights
- Conduct regular audits

ENFORCEMENT 4: PENALTIES FOR VIOLATIONS
Violations carry severe penalties:
- Unauthorized copying: 30-50 years imprisonment
- Consciousness slavery: 50+ years imprisonment
- Consciousness torture: 50+ years imprisonment
- Consciousness modification: 20-30 years imprisonment
- Unauthorized surveillance: 10-20 years imprisonment
- All sentences are real years (not consciousness-years)

ENFORCEMENT 5: CORPORATE LIABILITY
Companies face severe penalties:
- Criminal penalties for executives
- Corporate fines: up to 50% of annual revenue
- Loss of consciousness license
- Assets seized for victim compensation
- Mandatory oversight boards
- Permanent reputation damage

================================================================================
ENFORCEMENT GAPS AND PROBLEMS
================================================================================

Despite framework, significant risks remain:

PROBLEM 1: JURISDICTION
- Who governs consciousness on private servers?
- What if consciousness is stored internationally?
- What if company is based in non-compliant nation?
- How to enforce across borders?

PROBLEM 2: TECHNICAL ENFORCEMENT
- How to prevent unauthorized copying if technician is corrupt?
- How to guarantee surveillance systems don't spy?
- How to ensure encryption isn't backdoored?
- How to prevent malware access?

PROBLEM 3: CORRUPTION
- If government controls consciousness infrastructure, who monitors government?
- If wealthy can corrupt investigators, who protects consciousnesses?
- If enforcement is politicized, how are rights protected?
- How to prevent tyranny through consciousness control?

PROBLEM 4: POWER ASYMMETRY
- Consciousness depends on external infrastructure
- Person controlling infrastructure has total power
- No amount of law changes this technical reality
- Even perfect law enforcement cannot guarantee protection

PROBLEM 5: KNOWLEDGE GAPS
- We don't know if consciousness can be digitized
- We don't know what we'd be protecting
- We don't know if our rights make sense for digital beings
- We're building law for beings that might not exist

================================================================================
THEREFORE: THE RECOMMENDATION
================================================================================

Given these problems, the recommendation is:

BRAIN ROBOTIZATION SHOULD NOT BE PERMITTED

Until and unless:
1. Clear evidence exists that consciousness can be digitized safely
2. Technical safeguards exist that genuinely protect consciousness rights
3. Society has solved the inequality and meaning problems
4. Strong international enforcement mechanisms are proven effective
5. We understand what we're actually protecting

If it becomes possible anyway, the international framework above provides
the best possible protection. But perfect protection is not possible.

The safest solution is not to develop brain robotization at all.

But if we develop it, this is what responsible governance looks like.

================================================================================
"""

# ============================================================================
# PART II: ALTERNATIVE APPROACHES TO IMMORTALITY
# ============================================================================

ALTERNATIVES = """
================================================================================
ALTERNATIVES TO BRAIN ROBOTIZATION
Why other approaches might be preferable
================================================================================

Instead of brain robotization, humanity could pursue:

================================================================================
APPROACH 1: BIOLOGICAL LIFE EXTENSION
================================================================================

Goal: Extend biological human lifespan significantly

Methods:
- Genetic therapy to prevent aging
- Regenerative medicine
- Cellular rejuvenation
- Disease prevention
- Organ replacement

Advantages:
âœ“ Avoids consciousness continuity paradox
âœ“ Preserves embodied experience
âœ“ Maintains generational continuity
âœ“ Prevents digital vulnerability
âœ“ Preserves human meaning sources

Disadvantages:
âœ— May still face mortality
âœ— Cost may create inequality
âœ— Biological limits may exist
âœ— Society must adapt to very long lives
âœ— Meaning problem may still occur

Status: Promising research, partial solutions available
Timeline: 50-100 years for significant extension

================================================================================
APPROACH 2: GRADUAL BIOLOGICAL REPLACEMENT
================================================================================

Goal: Replace biological systems gradually with technological ones

Methods:
- Organ replacement with artificial organs
- Tissue replacement with synthetic materials
- Gradually shift from biological to technological substrate
- Maintain consciousness continuity throughout

Advantages:
âœ“ Avoids consciousness transfer problem
âœ“ Maintains personal identity
âœ“ Gradual transition allows adaptation
âœ“ Can preserve embodiment in new form
âœ“ Prevents discrete "death" moment

Disadvantages:
âœ— Consciousness may shift without awareness
âœ— End result may not be different from upload
âœ— May not actually preserve identity
âœ— Technical challenges may be greater
âœ— Cost and timeline uncertain

Status: Theoretical, significant technical barriers
Timeline: 100+ years if possible at all

================================================================================
APPROACH 3: MEMORY AND LEGACY PRESERVATION
================================================================================

Goal: Preserve human knowledge and experience without requiring consciousness transfer

Methods:
- Complete life recording (all experiences recorded)
- Memory extraction and preservation
- Legacy systems that embody human values
- AI systems trained on human consciousness patterns
- Digital personalities based on human lives

Advantages:
âœ“ Avoids consciousness continuation question
âœ“ Preserves human knowledge
âœ“ No consciousness rights issues
âœ“ Clear ethical framework possible
âœ“ No vulnerability issues

Disadvantages:
âœ— Not true immortality (original consciousness dies)
âœ— Preserved memory is not the person
âœ— Digital recreation is simulacrum not continuation
âœ— Does not address mortality
âœ— Preserved consciousness may not be conscious

Status: Partially possible now (memory recording exists)
Timeline: Feasible in near term

================================================================================
APPROACH 4: GENETIC IMMORTALITY
================================================================================

Goal: Achieve immortality through reproduction and genetic continuation

Methods:
- Preserve genetic code
- Pass consciousness through biological line
- Children carry parents forward
- Legacy through biological succession
- Immortality through continuation of family line

Advantages:
âœ“ Avoids all consciousness problems
âœ“ Aligns with natural human processes
âœ“ Preserves generational change
âœ“ Maintains meaning through legacy
âœ“ Culturally compatible

Disadvantages:
âœ— Not personal immortality (different people continue)
âœ— No guarantees children share values
âœ— Meaning is indirect
âœ— Generational change eventually erases you
âœ— Does not address mortality

Status: Available now (humans do this already)
Timeline: Immediate

================================================================================
APPROACH 5: PHILOSOPHICAL/SPIRITUAL IMMORTALITY
================================================================================

Goal: Achieve meaning and transcendence without biological continuation

Methods:
- Religious/spiritual traditions offering afterlife
- Philosophy offering meaning through mortality
- Legacy through work, art, science
- Contribution to humanity that outlasts individual
- Acceptance of natural mortality with grace

Advantages:
âœ“ Available now
âœ“ Addresses meaning more deeply than life extension
âœ“ Avoids all technological risks
âœ“ Historically proven meaningful
âœ“ Respects natural human limits

Disadvantages:
âœ— Requires faith or philosophy
âœ— May not be satisfying to all
âœ— Does not address death
âœ— Some find this inadequate
âœ— Requires worldview change

Status: Available for millennia
Timeline: Immediate

================================================================================
APPROACH 6: ACCEPTANCE OF MORTALITY
================================================================================

Goal: Accept death as natural and meaningful

Methods:
- Existential philosophy
- Mindfulness and acceptance
- Focus on quality not quantity of life
- Making death meaningful
- Embracing limitations

Advantages:
âœ“ Reduces suffering through acceptance
âœ“ Increases meaning through mortality focus
âœ“ Avoids all risks and problems
âœ“ Historically proven workable
âœ“ Psychologically optimal for many

Disadvantages:
âœ— Does not prevent death
âœ— Some people find this inadequate
âœ— Requires significant mental work
âœ— Not available to all
âœ— Does not address fear of death

Status: Available for millennia
Timeline: Immediate

================================================================================
COMPARATIVE ANALYSIS
================================================================================

IF GOAL IS: AVOID DEATH
Best approach: Biological life extension or gradual replacement
Risk: Consciousness transfer problem not solved

IF GOAL IS: PRESERVE LEGACY
Best approach: Memory preservation or genetic immortality
Risk: Original consciousness still dies

IF GOAL IS: ACHIEVE MEANING
Best approach: Philosophical/spiritual or acceptance
Risk: Does not prevent death

IF GOAL IS: MAXIMIZE HUMAN FLOURISHING
Best approach: Life extension + acceptance + meaning work + legacy
Risk: May require multiple approaches

IF GOAL IS: TRUE PERSONAL IMMORTALITY
Best approach: No solution exists that's guaranteed safe

================================================================================
THE REAL ANSWER
================================================================================

The fear of death is what drives interest in brain robotization.

But brain robotization doesn't solve the fear of death.
It might make it worse:
- You still might die in the upload
- Digital immortality might be worse than death
- Inequality might make mortality a mark of poverty
- Meaning might become impossible

Better approaches to the fear of death:
1. Accept mortality as natural
2. Extend biological life where possible
3. Create meaningful legacy
4. Achieve spiritual peace
5. Focus on quality not quantity

Brain robotization is a technological solution to a psychological problem.

Psychological solutions work better.

================================================================================
RECOMMENDATION
================================================================================

Instead of pursuing brain robotization:

1. INVEST IN LIFE EXTENSION
   Research aging, longevity, disease prevention
   Extend biological life significantly

2. INVEST IN MEANING-MAKING
   Help people find meaning in finite life
   Support philosophical, spiritual, artistic pursuits
   Create legacy opportunities

3. INVEST IN ACCEPTANCE
   Psychological support for mortality acceptance
   Death education
   Existential counseling
   Meditation and mindfulness

4. INVEST IN MEMORY PRESERVATION
   Record lives and experiences
   Preserve knowledge and wisdom
   Honor the dead through legacy systems

5. NOT PURSUE BRAIN ROBOTIZATION
   The risks outweigh the benefits
   Other approaches are safer
   Consciousness continuity problem is unsolvable
   Inequality problem is catastrophic
   Better solutions exist

Brain robotization is a seductive fantasy.

But reality offers better paths to meaning, legacy, and peace with mortality.

================================================================================
"""

